XVIII. 1 Also controversies often occur respecting acceptance made for another: in which a distinction is to be made between a promise made to me, to give a thing to another, and a promise con- veyed in the name of him to whom the thing is to be given. If the pro- mise is made to me, omitting the consideration whether the performanee of the promise is to my private interest, (which was introduced by the Roman lam) it seems, by the Law of Nature, that Ι acquire the right of effecting‚ by my acceptance, that the right promised pass to the other person: so that in the intermediate time the promise cannot be revoked by the promiser3 but Ι, to whom the promise was made, have power to remit it. For that sense is not repugnant to Natural Law, and agrees best with the words of such a promise: nor is it a matter uninteresting to me, that a person should acquire a benefit through me.
